INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("272", "1", "2012-08-29 10:54:42", "2012-08-29 10:54:42", "<strong>Anyone want to buy a kidney?</strong>\n\nI’ve been toying with the idea of buying a new toy for a couple of months now. Not that there’s much wrong with my current bike – I love it, in fact it’s just.....well, four years old and there are shinier, newer bikes out there which would obviously make me a better, more skilful, fitter rider.\n\nWhen you’re a cyclist, boarder, surfer, skater or do any other sport which involves a piece of equipment you’re bombarded by “The Next Best Thing” which promises to make you stronger, faster, better, higher, gnarlier or more attractive to the opposite sex.\n\nAnd I have fallen in love.\n\nI’d never really paid much attention to Transition bikes before, as they always seem a bit too exotic and niche to be a realistic bike for me. Guys in videos who can ride a shit load better than me will flash the frame decal whilst doing some super slow-mo tabletop, whilst winking at the camera, as if to say “Yeah, I deserve this bike because I can do this on it. Can you?”\n\nThis beauty is the Transition Bikes Carbon Fibre Covert – although I think the Covert part is ironic with this paint job.\n\nIf fact, there’s a lot of irony around this bike – the fact that the technology they’ve created to build the thing is “COCK and BALLS” technology (explained in this very informative film: <a href=\"https://vimeo.com/45041994\">https://vimeo.com/45041994</a>)\n\nPerhaps the most ironic thing is the simple fact that I must have it.  However the frame and shock only price is a monsterous £2,399 – with a full bike build starting at £4,750!?!\n\nI have a plan to eventually own this bike but it involves selling an internal organ or two, which - ironically – means I’ll have to recover before I’ll be able to ride it.\n\nDamn!", "Transition Covert", "", "inherit", "closed", "open", "", "264-revision-4", "", "", "2012-08-29 10:54:42", "2012-08-29 10:54:42", "", "264", "http://escpd.com/264-revision-4/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
